      "reasoning": "The mutation changes the grid size calculation from (size + block_size - 1) / block_size to (size + block_size + 1) / block_size. This increases the number of launched thread blocks by exactly 1 when size is not a multiple of block_size, and by 1 even when size is a multiple of block_size (since the +1 makes the numerator larger). However, the kernel itself checks 'if (idx < size)' before writing to output, so any extra threads launched beyond the actual number of elements simply do nothing. The output tensor is pre-allocated with torch::empty_like(input), so uninitialized memory is never read. For the fixed input shape [16, 16384], size = 262144, which is exactly divisible by block_size=256 (262144 / 256 = 1024). The original grid_size = 1024, the mutant grid_size = (262144 + 256 + 1) / 256 = 1025. The extra block (1024 threads) all have idx >= size, so they are no-ops. No matter what values are in the input tensor, the output is bit-identical because the same valid threads compute the same ReLU operation. Layer 2's 100 random tests already covered all possible value distributions, and all were bitwise identical. Thus the mutant is truly equivalent.",
